@namedgraph [`StreamManager`](https://jena.apache.org/documentation/javadoc/arq/org/apache/jena/riot/system/stream/StreamManager.html) now provides the mapping pieces, so you'd do something like:

```
try (TypedInputStream input = RDFDataMgr.open(filenameOrUri, yourStreamManager)) {
  Model model = new YourDesiredModelImpl();
  Lang lang = RDFDataMgr.determineLang(filenameOrUri, input.getContentType(), fallbackLang);
  return RDFDataMgr.read(model, input, input.getBaseURI(), lang);
}
```

### Requirements
Provide (retain) Java interfaces for HTTP-based RDF specifications (Linked Data, SPARQL Protocol, Graph Store Protocol) that satisfy the REST [Uniform Interface constraint](https://www.ics.uci.edu/~fielding/pubs/dissertation/rest_arch_style.htm#sec_5_1_5), i.e. that the interface on both the client and server side should be the same.

That makes implementation of components such as proxies trivial:

    class GSPProxyServer implements DatasetAccessor
    {

        public Response get()
        {
            return getBackend().getClient().get();
        }

        public Response post(Model model)
        {
            return getBackend().getClient().post(model);
        }

        ...

    }
    
    class GraphStoreClient implements DatasetAccessor
    {
        public Response get()
        {
            return ClientBuilder.newClient().target(getURI())....get();
        }

        ...
    }

Server- or client-specific interfaces can naturally extend the uniform interfaces.
It should work with `StreamRDF` as well.

### Compatibility
IMO a great strategic advantage would be making these interfaces JAX-RS compatible. `javax.ws.rs-api` is used by almost 2500 artifacts according to Maven central.
Jena does not need to depend on Jersey or another JAX-RS implementation, it should be possible to depend on the [javax.ws.rs-api](https://mvnrepository.com/artifact/javax.ws.rs/javax.ws.rs-api) only. However Jersey is probably the primary JAX-RS implementation.
A weaker compatibility would be reusing the JAX-RS API under Jena's namespace, making it a drop-in replacement.

### Prior work
This approach is implemented in [AtomGraph Core](https://github.com/AtomGraph/Core) using Jersey. We are willing to contribute its code - it is Apache-licensed already.

I asked what requirements it places on Jena for the flexibility for there to be a JAX RS API module.

As that exists in AtomGraph, it is clearly possible.

The rest seems to be able stability of specific interfaces, accentuated by jumping from Jena 3.0.1 to Jena current.

> Provide (retain) Java interfaces 

Nothing is being removed.

`DatasetAccessor` is still there.

There is a better IMO interface than `DatasetAccessor` in `RDFDatasetConnection extends RDFDatasetAccessConnection`. It reflects experience with `DatasetAccessor`. 

There is a split into "read" and "read-write" so that "read" can be provided on its own. Compile time robustness not "UnsupportedOperationException".

Better names to be task focused. "fetch" because "get" is more common as getter in Java and some IDE tools do rely on that.
Remove the unnecessary "Model".
`add` -> `load` -- hopefully clearer because it has been a source of questions. YMMV.

The conversion of `DatasetAccessor` to `RDFDatasetConnection`::
```
    @Override public default Model getModel() { return fetch();}
    @Override public default Model getModel(String graphName) { return fetch(graphName);}
    @Override public default boolean containsModel(String graphName) { return true; }
    @Override public default void putModel(Model model) { put(model); }
    @Override public default void putModel(String name, Model model) { put(name, model); }
    @Override public default void deleteDefault() { delete(); }
    @Override public default void deleteModel(String name) { delete(name); }
    @Override public default void add(Model model) { load(model); }
    @Override public default void add(String name, Model model) { load(name, model); }
```

> why FileManager is being deprecated

It's not. Some operations are deprecated.

It's still in `OntDocumentManager` because of the Jena module structure (i.e. legacy).

At runtime, the global `FileManager` is actually an `AdapterFileManager` and the machinery is a `StreamManager`.

> We are willing to contribute its code

Great but as I asked last time, what advantage is there in making it part of Jena? It has a cost - it has to be maintained and it slows Jena evolution down. Does it have it's own community around the code to support it? Is there a community of users to become contributors?
